    q: 'Which flowers are most dangerous to cats?',
    a: 'True lilies (Lilium and Hemerocallis genera — Easter, Tiger, Asiatic, Stargazer, Oriental, daylily) are the single most dangerous flowers for cats. Any part — petal, leaf, pollen on fur, even the vase water — can cause fatal kidney failure within 72 hours. Other lethal flowers for cats include lily of the valley, foxglove, oleander, and azalea/rhododendron.',
  },
  {
    q: 'Are roses safe for dogs and cats?',
    a: 'Yes — roses (Rosa spp.) are listed as non-toxic by the ASPCA. The flesh of the flower and stem will not poison dogs or cats. The thorns can still cause cuts, choking, or perforation, so stripped or thornless roses are safer in a pet household.',
  },
  {
    q: 'My cat just chewed on a lily petal — what do I do?',
    a: 'Treat it as an emergency. Call your vet or the ASPCA Animal Poison Control Center at (888) 426-4435 (US) or the Pet Poison Helpline at (855) 764-7661 immediately. Do not wait for symptoms — once kidney failure starts, the prognosis drops sharply. Bring the plant or a clear photo to the appointment.',
  },
  {
    q: 'Are tulips toxic to dogs?',
    a: 'Yes, tulips contain tulipalin A and B which cause vomiting, drooling, and depression in dogs. The bulb is significantly more toxic than the cut flower, so dogs that dig in the garden are most at risk. A cut tulip in a vase is lower-risk but still worth keeping out of reach.',
  },
  {
    q: 'What is the safest bouquet to send a household with a cat?',
    a: 'A bouquet built around roses, sunflowers, snapdragons, lisianthus, gerbera daisies, stock, statice, freesia, orchids, and plain greens like ruscus, leatherleaf, or eucalyptus (eucalyptus is a mild irritant — see notes). Always avoid ALL true lilies (Lilium / Hemerocallis), even one stem, in a cat household.',
  },
  {
    q: 'Is lavender safe for dogs and cats?',
    a: 'The lavender plant itself causes only mild GI upset if eaten, but concentrated lavender essential oil is significantly more toxic and is responsible for most lavender poisoning calls — never apply lavender essential oil to pets or use it in a closed-room diffuser around cats.',
  },
  {
    q: 'Where does this data come from?',
    a: 'Severity ratings on this tool are based on the ASPCA Toxic and Non-Toxic Plants database and the Pet Poison Helpline. It is a quick reference, not veterinary advice — always call a vet or pet poison control if your animal has actually ingested something. Linked ASPCA pages are referenced on each entry where available.',
  },
  {
    q: 'Can I prevent pet poisoning by just placing flowers up high?',
    a: 'Helpful but not foolproof, especially for cats — they jump and knock things over. Pollen drops onto surfaces and gets on fur, then is licked off; water tipped from a vase contains lily toxins; chewed leaves fall to the floor. The only fully safe option for a cat household is to never bring true lilies into the home at all, and to keep moderate-toxicity flowers in rooms the cat cannot access.',
  },
